<section>
    <h1>About Stackmark</h1>
    <p>Stackmark is a simple idea built from a very real problem: developers save a lot of links… and then forget why they saved them.</p>
    <p>Bookmarks pile up. Tabs get lost. That one helpful article disappears when you actually need it.</p>
    <p>Stackmark is designed to fix that.</p>
    <p>Instead of just saving links, you can add context — a short note explaining why something matters, what problem it solves, or when you might use it again. It turns a collection of bookmarks into something closer to a personal knowledge base.</p>
    <h2>Why I built it</h2>
    <p>While learning and working with different technologies, I found myself constantly saving resources — documentation, tutorials, answers — but rarely revisiting them effectively. Without context, they lost their value.</p>
    <p>Stackmark is an attempt to solve that in a simple, focused way.</p>
    <h2>Who it's for</h2>
    <p>Stackmark is built for developers who:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>regularly learn from online resources</li>
        <li>want to organise knowledge, not just collect links</li>
        <li>prefer something lightweight and focused over complex tools</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>What it focuses on</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Saving links quickly</li>
        <li>Adding meaningful context</li>
        <li>Organising with tags</li>
        <li>Making things easy to find later</li>
    </ul>
    <p>No clutter, no unnecessary features, just a tool to help you actually use what you save.</p>
</section>